<h2><a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.php?id=1192" title="Curling men win bronze... I wish I could play"> Curling men win bronze... I wish I could play</a></h2>

<div class="entry">


     

  	<p>Congrats to the American men&#8217;s curling team who <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/02/24/AR2006022400483_pf.html">pulled out a bronze medal</a> on the final throw of the match against Great Britain. The Americans had not placed in major competitions since 1978.</p>
	<p>Curling is a great sport that&#8217;s both social and extremely strategic. I like the description of &#8220;chess on ice.&#8221;</p>
	<p>I was lucky to play it when I was in college&#8212;I took it for my required phys.ed class. To this day I wish I could play it again.</p>
	<p>Indeed, it is probably the only sport I have ever done well at for more than one game. I had one good game of bowling (210) and one good game playing goalie in soccer (same game I broke my hand), but in curling worked for me. </p>
	<p>During the class I was the last of my team to try his hand at skipping, essentially directing the game strategy. Our team close to the basement of the class league, but when I took over and we started winning so we stopped rotating. We advanced to fourth place and squeaked into the playoffs. We actually made it to the championship game and had a chance to take the &#8220;gold&#8221; until the last end when the other team lined up their rocks just right and we couldn&#8217;t get into the target area inside their stones.</p>
	<p>Mind you, I think I was better at the strategy than sweeping so getting me out of that probably helped as well. Nonetheless, I &#8220;won a silver&#8221; out of a bunch of college kids learning to play curling.</p>
	<p>That&#8217;s the only sports hero story you will <strong>ever</strong> hear from me.</p>

 
<div class="line"></div>

